IS  - 2376-0605 (Electronic)
IS  - 2376-0605 (Linking)
VI  - 5
IP  - 4
DP  - 2019 Jul-Aug
TI  - PARKINSONISM AS AN ATYPICAL MANIFESTATION OF PRIMARY HYPERPARATHYROIDISM.
PG  - e244-e246
LID - 10.4158/ACCR-2018-0504 [doi]
AB  - OBJECTIVE: Primary hyperparathyroidism (PHPT) occurs as a result of 
      hyperfunctional parathyroid glands resulting in an elevation of serum calcium 
      levels. The association between hypoparathyroidism and parkinsonism have been 
      frequently reported in the literature, while evidence of hyperparathyroidism 
      associated with parkinsonism is rare. METHODS: The present study reports a case 
      of a patient that had PHPT and developed symptoms of parkinsonism. RESULTS: A 
      75-year-old female patient with a history of diabetes mellitus, dyslipidemia, and 
      systemic arterial hypertension presented to the emergency room due to unexplained 
      drowsiness. Her serum calcium at the time was 14.2 mg/dL. A cervical ultrasound 
      was performed, and the presence of a 2.5 × 1.9-cm nodule in the left lower 
      parathyroid region was identified. Three days later, scintigraphy with the use of 
      sestamibi showed an increased capture of the marker in the same region, 
      suggesting parathyroid hyperfunction. During hospitalization, the patient 
      developed symptoms of parkinsonism. A left inferior parathyroidectomy was 
      performed, with normalization of serum calcium levels and a remission of 
      drowsiness, in addition to a significant improvement in parkinsonian symptoms. 
      The patient remained free of parkinsonism over 3 years of follow up. CONCLUSION: 
      Parathyroidectomy can provide a significant remission of parkinsonism in a 
      patient with PHPT. Even though it is rare, the relation between parkinsonism and 
      PHPT exists.
