TI  - Systemic correlates of angiographic coronary artery disease.
PG  - e4322
LID - 10.1371/journal.pone.0004322 [doi]
LID - e4322
AB  - Coronary angiography allows a direct evaluation of coronary anatomy. The aim of 
      the present investigation was to search for correlations between the magnitude of 
      coronary artery disease, as assessed by angiography, and a number of systemic 
      parameters. A group of 116 patients (80 male, 36 female) with coronary heart 
      disease diagnosed by angiography, aged 62.0+/-10.5 years, was the subject of an 
      observational study. Correlation and linear regression analysis using coronary 
      artery disease burden (CADB - sum of the percentage of the luminal stenosis 
      encountered in all the lesions of the coronary arterial trees) as dependent 
      variable, and age, sex, plasma calcium, phosphorus, magnesium, glucose, HDL 
      cholesterol, LDL cholesterol, triglycerides, uric acid, estimated glomerular 
      filtration rate and body mass index as independent variables, were carried out. 
      Significant correlation values versus CADB were seen with age (r 0.19, p 0.04), 
      uric acid (r 0.18, p 0.048) and fasting plasma glucose (r 0.33, p<0.001). Linear 
      regression analysis, yielding a global significance level of 0.002, showed a 
      significant value for glucose (p 0.018) and for sex (0.008). In conclusion, among 
      several systemic parameters studied, plasma glucose was found to be correlated to 
      coronary artery atherosclerosis lesions.
