TI  - [Selected parameters of bone metabolism in hemodialyzed and peritoneally dialyzed 
      patients].
PG  - 711-3
AB  - Renal osteodystrophy is a metabolic bone disease occurring in patients with 
      end-stage renal failure. The aim of the study was to compare serum concentrations 
      of some bone markers in hemodialysed (HD) patients and in patients undergoing 
      continuous ambulatory peritoneal dialysis (CADO). We studied two groups of 
      patients with end-stage renal failure: 52 hemodialysed individuals aged 24-74 
      years and 19 peritoneally dialysed patients aged 20-70 years. Serum calcium and 
      phosphate concentration, cholesterol, triglycerides, total protein, albumin, 
      alkaline phosphatase, urea before and after HD, urea in CADO patients were 
      determined by standard laboratory methods. Serum PTH, osteocalcin, 1,25(OH)2D3 
      and insulin-like growth factor (IGF-1) concentrations were measured by 
      commercially available radioimmunoassay. Serum tumor necrosis factor (TNF-alpha) 
      and interleukin-1 (IL-1) concentrations were measured by ELISA. There were no 
      differences between serum concentrations of the studied bone markers in 
      hemodialysed patients and CAPD patients. All dialysed patients presented high 
      concentrations of serum PTH, osteocalcin, alkaline phosphatase activity, lower 
      serum IGF-1 concentration and normal serum calcitriol concentration. High serum 
      PTH and osteocalcin concentrations may indicate intensification of bone 
      synthesis, what is typical for osteitis fibrosa.
