DP  - 1975 Dec
TI  - The effect of anticonvulsant therapy on serum levels of 25-hydroxy-vitamin D, 
      calcium, and parathyroid hormone.
PG  - 1130-5
AB  - In 20 female patients treated for 2 to 37 years (mean :12) with anticonvulsant 
      drugs, low serum levels of 25-hydroxy-vitamin D (25-OH-D; 6.4 +/- 3.2 ng/ml M +/- 
      SD), relative hypocalcemia (9.2 +/- 0.4 mg/100 ml) and high levels of parathyroid 
      hormone (PTH 277 +/- 165 pg/ml) were found compared to an age-matched control 
      group (respectively 8.6 +/- 3.2 ng/ml, 9.6 +/- 0.3 mg/100 ml and 183 +/- 95 
      pg/ml) living in the same psychiatric clinic. A significant negative correlation 
      was found between total duration of treatment and either serum 25-OH-D or serum 
      calcium. After treatment with an oral vitamin D3 supplement (2000 IU/day) for 3 
      weeks, the serum 25-OH-D levels, although increased, remained lower than normal 
      in the epileptic group and neither hypocalcemia nor their secondary 
      hyperparathyroidism were corrected. These data confirm the occurrence of vitamin 
      D deficiency in patients treated with anticonvulsant drugs resulting in 
      hypocalcemia and secondary hyperparathyroidism.
